{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":5020,"record_hash":"sha256:77cb7b889d6e1453a1409114187715496e2880b1a3ee07087cf05b481ce96963","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:14:24.509Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] UUID-shaped secrets bypass redaction\\\" body=\\\"The non-secret exception is unconditional: a bare UUID value is preserved even when it appears under fields like `api_key`, `token`, or `secret`. UUID-shaped session tokens are common enough that this can leak a secret unexpectedly. POC-small fix: let sensitive field names override the UUID exemption, or only preserve UUIDs for known transcript ID fields.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=116 priority=2 confidence=0.78}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P3] Slash-inclusive candidates over-redact paths\\\" body=\\\"Including `/` in candidate bytes makes ordinary repo/file paths scan as one long entropy candidate. Some realistic paths cross the 4.0 threshold and would be replaced, losing important transcript context. A small fix would special-case obvious path-like values, or only keep `/` inside candidates when there are stronger token cues such as base64 padding/sign characters.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=119 end=123 priority=3 confidence=0.72}\\n\\n**Findings**\\n\\n- [P2] UUID-shaped secrets can bypass redaction at [redaction.rs:116](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:116). The code preserves UUID-ish values without considering the field name, so `{\\\"api_key\\\":\\\"[REDACTED:entropy]\\\"}` would be stored verbatim.\\n\\n- [P3] Path-like transcript data can be over-redacted because `/` is part of the candidate alphabet at [redaction.rs:119](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:119). That helps catch base64, but also turns long paths into high-entropy candidates.\\n\\nI did not see the code overstating guarantees: the module and the data-model notes consistently frame this as best-effort POC redaction, local-only, and not a publication policy. Review only; I did not run the test suite.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:14:24.509Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}